&lt;/edit&gt; <p></p><i>Edited by: <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/useijinmanasponge.showPublicProfile?language=EN>Seijin Manasponge</A> at: 2/7/02 12:00:34 pm<br></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub13.ezboard.com/ucasonmonk.showPublicProfile?language=EN>CasonMonk</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Registered User</span><br> <font color=#FF0000>(2/7/02 2:45:35 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub13.ezboard.com/fprexus95980rants.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=910.topic&index=35>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Rangers.</span><hr size=1> Many of the responses seem to be from high level rangers who have buffs and items that are generally not within reach of mid levels.  I will clarify the Ranger issue a bit for those interested in the high 30's low 40's.  <br>
<br>
Background:  Lvl 38 RNG  Lvl 38 MNK<br>
<br>
My hunting partner is a ranger.  You will rarely see any either of us online without the other one right there or on the way there.  <br>
<br>
Scenario:<br>
<br>
Monks are straight forward.  Damage. <br>
<br>
Ranger (in my instance)<br>
<br>
-Light buffs to enhance combat (They DO make a difference)<br>
<br>
-Light heals during downtime<br>
<br>
-minor DoT (It DOES speed things up)<br>
<br>
-SoW (makes travelling easier)<br>
<br>
-Snare (In dungeons, a true BLESSING)<br>
<br>
-Invis .. good for travelling to keep those pesky light blues from slowing you down<br>
<br>
-Forage (no more hungry monk - my ranger friend feeds me a few items at a time, so as to keep my weight down - and the food/drink stays with me when I log)<br>
<br>
-small nukes, which can help with pulling<br>
<br>
-AWESOME damage even when &quot;moderately&quot; equipped (Centi weapons, Ry'Gorr armor)<br>
<br>
-Aggro sharing without parallel<br>
<br>
-Track (to locate and identify the &quot;lay of the land&quot;)<br>
<br>
Example:<br>
<br>
We zone into a place like Overthere or Great Divide.  My ranger partner checks our buffs, tosses up track to find out what we are up against.  We find a nice pull spot, and I get to work.  9 times out of 10, a wandering caster or group will walk past, stop to stare at us &quot;pinballing&quot; the mob, (our term for making a mob turn back and forth during a fight because it had not &quot;locked&quot; aggro), and ask to join or us to join them.  <br>
<br>
We hit a dungeon, find a pull spot, I will grab the critter, ranger tags it, snare, stops taunting, I gain aggro back, mend, ranger retakes aggro, mob dies.  If too many adds come, I call the run, ranger bolts, I FD, when it is clear ranger returns we repeat the process. <br>
<br>
Result:<br>
<br>
Few deaths, great exp, and TONS of FUN.  From what I read it will only get better as we continue levelling.  Lastly, on raids, our traditional group is:<br>
<br>
WAR<br>
MNK<br>
RNG<br>
ENC<br>
SHM<br>
CLR<br>
<br>
Damage is obscene at our levels and our cleric friend complains that we are killing the mobs too fast.  (hehe)  My point is that maybe Rangers in the higher levels &quot;sucked&quot; a while back before some of the changes made, they ROCK IMHO.  <!--EZCODE EMOTICON START :) --><img src=http://www.ezboard.com/intl/aenglish/images/emoticons/smile.gif ALT=":)"><!--EZCODE EMOTICON END--> <br>
